>Latvian Encyclopedia</target><arg>2</arg><arg>137</arg></template></extension><space/>It became connected to the<space/><link><target>Berezina</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Dnieper</target></link><space/>rivers in the 19th century by a canal, which no longer functions. The Daugava forms part of the international border between Latvia and Belarus.</paragraph><paragraph>According to C.Michael Hogan, the Daugava river began experiencing environmental deterioration in the era of Soviet collective agriculture (producing considerable adverse water pollution runoff) and a wave of hydroelectric power projects.</paragraph><paragraph>There are three<space/><link><target>Hydroelectricity</target><part>hydroelectric</part></link><space/><link><target>dam</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>on the Daugava<space/><link><target>Rgas HES</target></link><space/>just upstream from<space/><link><target>Riga</target></link><space/>or<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>35</arg><arg>km</arg><arg>mi</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>from the mouth of the river,<space/><link><target>egums Hydro Power Plant</target><part>egums HPP</part></link><space/>another<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>35</arg><arg>km</arg><arg>mi</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>further up or<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>70</arg><arg>km</arg><arg>mi</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>from the mouth, and<space/><link><target>Pavias Hydro Power Plant</target><part>Pavias HPP</part></link><space/>another<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>37</arg><arg>km</arg><arg>mi</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>upstream or<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>107</arg><arg>km</arg><arg>mi</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>from the mouth. A fourth one,<space/><link><target>Daugava 1 Hydro Power Plant</target><part>Daugavpils HES</part></link>, has been planned but has faced strong opposition. Belarus plans to build several hydroelectric dams on the Belarusian part of Western Dvina.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Geography</heading><paragraph>The total catchment area of the river is<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>87900</arg><arg>km²</arg><arg>mi2</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template>,<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>33150</arg><arg>km²</arg><arg>mi2</arg><arg name="abbr">on</arg></template><space/>of which are within<space/><link><target>Belarus</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="statistics"></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>Etymology</heading><paragraph>The Latvian name for the river, &quot;Daugava&quot; originated from the ancient Baltic words for &quot;the great water&quot; (daudz dens).<template><target>citation needed</target><arg name="date">August 2012</arg></template><space/>The names for the Daugava in other languages; Dyna Dna Dwina Dvina - Vina have an unclear origin. This name is mentioned in the Viking sagas and the<space/><link><target>Chronicle of Nestor</target></link>.According to the<space/><link><target>Max Vasmer</target></link>'s Etymological Dictionary, the<space/><link><target>toponym</target></link><space/>Dvina clearly cannot stem from a<space/><link><target>Uralic language</target></link>, and it possibly comes from<space/><link><target>Indo-European languages</target><part>Indo-European</part></link><space/>word which used to mean<space/><italics>river</italics><space/>or<space/><italics>stream</italics>.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="last">Фасмер</arg><arg name="first">Макс</arg><arg name="script-title">ru:Этимологический словарь Фасмера</arg><arg name="url">http://starling.rinet.ru/cgi-bin/response.cgi?root</arg><arg name="language">Russian</arg><arg name="page">161</arg></template></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>Cities, towns and settlements</heading><heading level='3'>Russia</heading><paragraph><link><target>Andreapol</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Zapadnaya Dvina</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Velizh</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='3'>Belarus</heading><paragraph><link><target>Ruba</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Vitsebsk</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Beshankovichy</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Polatsk</target></link><space/>with<space/><link><target>Boris stones</target></link><space/>strewn in the vicinity,<space/><link><target>Navapolatsk</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Dzisna</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Verkhnedvinsk</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Druya</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='3'>Latvia</heading><paragraph><link><target>Krslava</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Daugavpils</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Lvni</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Jkabpils</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Pavias</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Aizkraukle</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Jaunjelgava</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Lielvrde</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Kegums</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Ogre, Latvia</target><part>Ogre</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Ikile</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Salaspils</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Riga</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Crossings</heading><heading level='3'>Belarus</heading><paragraph><link><target>Kirov Bridge</target></link>, Vitebsk.</paragraph><heading level='3'>Latvia</heading><paragraph><link><target>Southern Bridge</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Island Bridge, Riga</target><part>Island Bridge</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Railway Bridge, Riga</target><part>Railway Bridge</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Stone Bridge, Riga</target><part>Stone Bridge</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Shroud Bridge</target></link>, Riga.</paragraph><paragraph>Dams of<space/><link><target>Rgas HES</target></link>,<space/><link><target>egums Hydro Power Plant</target><part>egums HPP</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Pavias Hydro Power Plant</target><part>Pavias HPP</part></link></paragraph><paragraph>Vienbas tilts, Daugavpils</paragraph><heading level='2'>Main tributaries</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Aiviekste River</target><part>Aiviekste</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Paata</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Kasplya River</target><part>Kasplya</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Mezha River (Western Dvina)</target><part>Mezha</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Dysna</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Prse</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>Reflist</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Further reading</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="title">Latvia<space/></arg><arg name="author">Richard C. Frucht<space/></arg><arg name="author2">Aldis Purs<space/></arg><arg name="work">Eastern Europe<space/></arg><arg name="pages">115<space/></arg><arg name="publisher">[[ABC-CLIO]]<space/></arg><arg name="accessdate">2009-08-01</arg></template></listitem></list><list type='bullet'><listitem>C.Michael Hogan. 2012.<space/><link type='external' href='http://www.eoearth.org/article/Daugava_River?topic=78166'>''Daugava River''. Encyclopedia of Earth. Eds. P.Saundry &amp; C.J.Cleveland. National Council for Science and the Environment. Washington DC</link></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>coord</target><arg>57</arg><arg>3</arg><arg>42</arg><arg>N</arg><arg>24</arg><arg>1</arg><arg>50</arg><arg>E</arg><arg name="display">title</arg></template><template><target>Commons category</target><arg>Daugava</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Riga Cityscape</target></templat